'''Charles Joseph Sophy''' (born on October 2, 1960), best known as Dr. Charles Sophy, [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine|DO]], is a [[Los Angeles]] based [[psychiatrist]], and Medical Director for the County of Los Angeles Department of Children and Family Services. He is the author of ''Side By Side The Revolutionary Mother-Daughter Program for Conflict-Free Communication'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/side-by-side-charles-sophy/1103676641 |title=Side by Side: The Revolutionary Mother-Daughter Program for Conflict-Free Communication  |author= |date= |work= |publisher=Barnesandnoble.com llc |accessdate=2 November 2012}}</ref> and has appeared on several nationwide [[television]] broadcasts, [[radio]] broadcasts and numerous print and on-line publications.<ref name="Charles"/>

== Early life and education ==
Charles Sophy was born in [[Pottsville, Pennsylvania]] to parents Charles Joseph Sophy and Renee Marie Joseph.  He has one brother, Matthew Charles Sophy. He is of [[Lebanese American|Lebanese]] descent.

Sophy attended high school at Nativity B.V.M. High School in [[Pottsville, PA]] and obtained his Bachelor of Science in Biological Sciences at [[Saint Joseph’s University]] in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] in 1982.  He graduated from [[Philadelphia College of Osteopathic Medicine]] in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania in 1986, and completed his internship and family practice residency at the Metropolitan Hospital/Springfield Hospital in Springfield, Pennsylvania. He completed his Adult Psychiatry residency at [[Norristown State Hospital]] in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania<ref name="Charles">{{cite web |url=http://www.osteopathic.org/inside-aoa/news-and-publications/media-center/expert-sources/Pages/charles-sophy.aspx |title=Charles J Sophy, DO |author= |date= |work= |publisher=American Osteopathic Association |accessdate=2 November 2012}}</ref> followed by a fellowship for Child and Adolescent Psychiatry at [[Hahnemann University Hospital]] in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://republicanherald.com/news/hollywood-psychiatrist-sets-author-event-at-fairlane-1.649071?localLinksEnabled=false |title=Hollywood psychiatrist sets author event at Fairlane |author= |date=2010 |work= |publisher=republicanherald.com |accessdate=2 November 2012}}</ref>

== Career ==
Sophy is a licensed<ref>[http://www2.dca.ca.gov/pls/wllpub/WLLQRYNA$LCEV2.QueryView?P_LICENSE_NUMBER=6205&P_LTE_ID=1030 Osteopathic Medical Board of California - License # 20A6205]</ref> [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine]] and is board certified in Family Practice, Adult Psychiatry and Child/Adolescent Psychiatry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harpercollinsspeakersbureau.com/speaker/dr-charles-sophy.aspx |title=Dr. Charles Sophy, HarperCollins Speaker |publisher=Harper Collins Speakers Bureau |date= |accessdate=2012-06-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dr. Charles Sophy |url=http://www.vitals.com/doctors/Dr_Charles_Sophy |title=Dr. Charles Sophy, DO - Child & Adolescent Psychiatrist, Family Practitioner - Beverly Hills, CA - Family Medicine |publisher=Vitals.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-21}}</ref>

He serves as the Medical Director for the County of Los Angeles Department of Children and Family Services.  On November 6, 2008 Zimmer Children's Museum presented him the Discovery Award for Leadership, Vision and Commitment to the Community.
He is a member of the following organizations: [[American Psychiatric Association]], [[American Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry]], American College of Neuropsychiatry, [[American Osteopathic Association]], [[American Medical Association]], [[American College of Family Practitioners]], and the California Osteopathic Medical Association.<ref name="drsophy1">{{cite web|url=http://www.drsophy.com/about/professional-history/ |title=Professional History « Dr.Sophy.com |publisher=Drsophy.com |date= |accessdate=2010-02-01}}</ref>

He recently published his first book, ''Side By Side The Revolutionary Mother-Daughter Program for Conflict-Free Communication'', Harper Collins, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sophy |first=Charles |url=http://www.harpercollins.com/books/9780061791574/Side_by_Side/index.aspx |title=Side by Side: The Revolutionary Mother-Daughter Program for Conflict-Free Communication by Charles Sophy, Brown Kogen |publisher=Harpercollins.com |date= |accessdate=2010-02-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canyon-news.com/artman2/publish/Canyon_People_51/Five_Questions_With_Dr_Sophy.php |title=Five Questions With Dr. Sophy |publisher=Canyon News |date=2009-08-22 |accessdate=2010-02-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/bloggers/dr-charles-sophy |title=Dr. Charles Sophy |publisher=Psychology Today |date=2010-02-02 |accessdate=2012-06-21}}</ref><ref>[http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/35201685/ns/today-today_books/?utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=twitter&utm_campaign=Feed%3A+msn%2FHTtC+(msnbc.com%3A+Women's+health) msnbbc  2/3/2010]</ref>

He first appeared on national television for PBS in the show ''A Place of Our Own'', and subsequently on other shows on several networks, including as ''[[Celebrity Rehab with Dr. Drew]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Juzwiak |first=Rich |url=http://blog.vh1.com/2008-10-31/the-celebreality-interview-dr-charles-sophy/ |title=The Celebreality Interview – Dr. Charles Sophy – &#124; VH1 Blog |publisher=Blog.vh1.com |date=2008-10-31 |accessdate=2012-06-21}}</ref> ''[[Sober House]]'', ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today Show]]'', ''[[Larry King Live]]'', ''[[The Rachael Ray Show]]'', ''[[Good Morning America]]'', ''[[Anderson Cooper 360°]]'', ''[[Headline News]]'', ''[[Inside Edition]]'', ''[[CBS Early Show]]'', ''[[The Real Housewives of Beverly Hills]]'', and ''[[Flipping Out]]''.

He is the child mental health expert on [[Videojug]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videojug.com/profile/USEX0032 |title=Dr. Charles Sophy - Featured User Profile |publisher=Videojug |date= |accessdate=2012-06-21}}</ref> where he has  addressed [[ADD]] and [[ADHD]] as well as other child mental health issues.<ref>{{cite web|author=Charles Sophy |url=http://www.videojug.com/interview/add-and-adhd |title=ADD And ADHD (Family & Education: Learning Disabilities) |publisher=Videojug.com |date=2007-05-15 |accessdate=2010-02-01}}</ref>

Dr. Sophy has achieved some notoriety among tax practitioners for having brought suit in the United States Tax Court. In Sophy v. Commissioner, he and the co-owner of their two homes sued because the [[Internal Revenue Service]] had limited the amount of their deductible home mortgage interest expense. The suit establishes that unmarried co-owners are limited to the same amount of deduction that a married couple would be, by establishing that the maximum allowable deduction is determined per residence, not per tax return.<ref>''Sophy v. Commissioner'', 138 T.C. No. 8 (March 5, 2012).</ref>

== Controversy ==
Dr. Sophy has been featured on the television series, [[The Insider (TV series)|The Insider]], where he psychoanalyzed [[Gary Coleman]] who had walked off the show after being accused of abusing his wife. Dr. Sophy, who had been invited on the show to share his expert opinion, said, "You're lucky he didn't hit someone here tonight," and "What I saw there needs medicine," comments which have been generally ridiculed{{by whom?|date=September 2012}} as Coleman displayed no signs of violence during the interview.<ref>http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8Ls3HHysFzE&feature=related</ref>

